  <static seed="446" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/LinearEquationApplications/MXPlusBWordProblem30.pg">
    <statement><p>A school purchased a batch of T-shirts from a company. The company charged <m>{\$6}</m> per T-shirt, and gave the school a <m>{\$50}</m> rebate. If the school had a net expense of <m>{\$2{,}590}</m> from the purchase, how many T-shirts did the school buy?</p>
<p>The school purchased <fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/> T-shirts.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>440</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>Let <m>x</m> be the number of T-shirts the school purchased.</p>
<p>Each T-shirt costs <m>{\$6}</m>, so <m>x</m> T-shirts cost <m>6x</m> dollars. After that expense, there was a rebate of 50 dollars.</p>
<p>Now we can write an equation:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 6x-50 = 2590 }</m></p>
<p>Next, we solve for <m>x</m>:</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
  6x -50 \amp = 2590 \\
  6x -50\mathbf{{}+50} \amp = 2590\mathbf{{}+50} \\
  6x      \amp = 2640 \\
  \frac{6x}{6} \amp = \frac{2640}{6} \\
  x   \amp = 440
\end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>The school purchased <m>440</m> T-shirts.</p>
</solution>
